// p74 — List + List concatenation + List.append_all (v3.15.0).
//
// Before v3.15.0, `xs + ys` on two Lists SIGSEGV'd at runtime
// (Sema typed the operator as Int via the numeric compatible-
// operands fallback; Codegen emitted raw integer add against
// what were actually List pointers, dereferencing them as ints).
// The user-side workaround was a manual loop over `__get` +
// `append`.
//
// v3.15.0 lands three pieces:
//
//   - Runtime: Core_Collections_List_List___add (fresh result)
//     and Core_Collections_List_List_append_all (in-place mutate).
//
//   - Library: extern bindings in
//     packages/typing/collections/list.quirk. `extend` is reserved
//     in Quirk for `extend Foo { ... }` declarations, so the
//     mutating form is `append_all` — descriptive, no name
//     collision.
//
//   - Sema: `+` on two List operands now types as `List` instead
//     of falling through to Int. Codegen gains a per-struct
//     method registry (`structMethodNodes`) so the operator-
//     overload dispatch can find `Core_Collections_List_List___add`
//     from a bare `List` operand-struct name. Same-struct gate
//     prevents the dispatch from misfiring on mixed-type ops
//     like `String + Double` (which still goes through the
//     legacy coercion paths).

xs := [1, 2, 3]
ys := [4, 5, 6]

// `+` returns a fresh List, leaves originals intact.
zs := xs + ys
print(zs)              // = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
print(zs.length())     // = 6
print(xs)              // = [1, 2, 3]
print(ys)              // = [4, 5, 6]

// append_all mutates the receiver in place.
xs.append_all(ys)
print(xs)              // = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
print(xs.length())     // = 6

// `+` works on empty operands too.
print([] + [1, 2])     // = [1, 2]
print([3] + [])        // = [3]
